    "As in the standard SIS model, an infected individual can recover with probability μ.",
    "In absence of higher-order interactions, the SIS model undergoes a continuous transition from an absorbent state with a vanishing stationary fraction of infected individuals, ρ ⋆ = 0, to an active state with ρ ⋆ ≠ 0 88.",
    "In previous works 25, 40, it has been shown that the presence of higher-order interactions changes the nature of the transition from continuous to discontinuous, hence leading to the emergence of a region of bistability, where both the absorbent and active states co-exist.",
    "Here, we show that this does not occur for any hypergraph given a fixed interaction strength, but strongly depends on the level of intra-order hyperedge overlap.",
    "Figure 2 shows the results of stochastic simulations of the SIS model on hypergraphs with tunable intra-order hyperedge overlap."
